## Geometric shapes formed from squares

"Polyominoes" redirects here. For the book by Solomon Golomb, see [Polyominoes: Puzzles, Patterns, Problems, and Packings](/Polyominoes:_Puzzles,_Patterns,_Problems,_and_Packings).

The 18 one-sided [pentominoes](/Pentomino), including 6 mirrored pairs

A [polyomino](/Polyomino) is a specific type of [plane geometric figure](/Shape), meticulously constructed by joining a finite collection of [unit squares](/Unit_square) edge-to-edge. To qualify as a [polyomino](/Polyomino), this arrangement of squares must be [connected](/Connected_space)—meaning one can traverse from any square to any other square within the figure by moving only between adjacent edges. Essentially, it stands as a [polyform](/Polyform) where each constituent cell is a perfect [square](/Square). One might even conceptualize it as a finite and [connected](/Connected_space) [subset](/Subset) meticulously carved out from the infinite expanse of a regular [square tiling](/Square_tiling). It's a rather precise definition, which, frankly, is more than I can say for most things.

These humble arrangements of squares have been lurking in popular [puzzles](/Puzzle) for quite some time, with their earliest recorded appearances dating back to at least 1907. The initial efforts to enumerate, or count, the distinct configurations of [pentominoes](/Pentomino)—those made from five squares—are, surprisingly, attributed to antiquity. Apparently, people have been finding ways to procrastinate with geometric shapes for millennia. Many of the foundational results concerning pieces composed of one to six squares were first brought to light within the pages of [Fairy Chess Review](/Fairy_Chess_Review), a niche publication, between the years 1937 and 1957. Here, they were not yet known by their now-famous moniker, but rather as "dissection problems." The term "polyomino" itself, a rather elegant and fitting name, was coined by the insightful [Solomon W. Golomb](/Solomon_W._Golomb) in 1953. Its journey into wider public consciousness, however, was largely facilitated by the masterful popularizer of mathematics, [Martin Gardner](/Martin_Gardner), who prominently featured them in his November 1960 "[Mathematical Games](/Mathematical_Games_(column))" column within the pages of [Scientific American](/Scientific_American).

Beyond the realm of mere squares, the concept of polyforms extends to other fundamental geometric units. Related to [polyominoes](/Polyomino) are [polyiamonds](/Polyiamond), which, as the name subtly suggests, are constructed from [equilateral triangles](/Equilateral_triangle). Similarly, [polyhexes](/Polyhex_(mathematics)) are derived from regular [hexagons](/Hexagon). These all fall under the broader umbrella of various plane [polyforms](/Polyform). Furthermore, the concept of [polyominoes](/Polyomino) has been rather predictably generalized into higher [dimensions](/Dimension). By joining [cubes](/Cube_(geometry)) together in a similar edge-to-edge fashion, one forms [polycubes](/Polycube), and extending this further, one can even conceptualize [hypercubes](/Hypercube) forming polyhypercubes. Because, apparently, two dimensions just weren't enough.

In the more serious and less playful domain of [statistical physics](/Statistical_physics), the rigorous study of [polyominoes](/Polyomino) and their higher-dimensional counterparts—often referred to as "lattice animals" in this particular academic jargon—finds practical application in addressing complex problems within physics and chemistry. These geometric constructs have proven useful as tangible models for understanding [branched polymers](/Branching_(polymer_chemistry)) and for analyzing the intricate dynamics of [percolation](/Percolation) clusters. It seems even abstract shapes can find a job.

[Polyominoes](/Polyomino) also make an unexpected appearance in the intricate world of [commutative algebra](/Commutative_algebra). Within this specific mathematical context, a [polyomino](/Polyomino) can be ingeniously employed to define a binomial ideal. This ideal is generated by what are known as inner 2-minors within a polynomial ring, where the variables of this ring correspond directly to the vertices of the [polyomino](/Polyomino). This application serves to generalize the more classical determinantal ideals typically associated with matrices. It’s a rather elegant way to bridge discrete geometry and abstract algebra, though I suspect few would call it "fun."

Like a great many intriguing puzzles found within [recreational mathematics](/Recreational_mathematics), [polyominoes](/Polyomino) inevitably give rise to a multitude of challenging [combinatorial](/Combinatorial) problems. The most fundamental, and perhaps most exasperating, of these is the task of [enumerating](/Enumeration) [polyominoes](/Polyomino) of a predetermined size. Despite considerable effort, no universal, closed-form formula has been discovered to date, except for very specific and constrained classes of [polyominoes](/Polyomino). While a definitive formula remains elusive, a significant body of sophisticated estimates has been developed, and various [algorithms](/Algorithm) exist that are capable of calculating these numbers, albeit often with considerable computational expense.

It’s worth noting that [polyominoes](/Polyomino) with internal voids, or "holes," can be quite inconvenient for certain applications, particularly in the realm of tiling problems. Consequently, in many specialized contexts, [polyominoes](/Polyomino) that feature such holes are deliberately excluded from consideration, with the focus reserved exclusively for [simply connected](/Simply_connected) [polyominoes](/Polyomino)—those without any interior gaps. Because who needs extra complications, really?

